WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:02.936
Let's create your first repository!

00:00:02.936 --> 00:00:05.648
It's an encrypted file at rest that

00:00:05.648 --> 00:00:08.359
turns into a fully isolated environment the

00:00:08.359 --> 00:00:09.908
moment you create it.

00:00:10.693 --> 00:00:13.602
On disk it's a single encrypted image.

00:00:13.602 --> 00:00:14.433
Once mounted,

00:00:14.433 --> 00:00:16.927
you get a dedicated Docker daemon,

00:00:16.927 --> 00:00:19.420
application data inside the encrypted volume,

00:00:19.420 --> 00:00:22.329
and loopback IPs that won't collide with

00:00:22.329 --> 00:00:24.407
anything else on the server.

00:00:27.692 --> 00:00:30.471
Time to create a 2 gigabyte encrypted

00:00:30.471 --> 00:00:32.060
repository on the server.

00:00:32.060 --> 00:00:34.839
A repository is a single encrypted file

00:00:34.839 --> 00:00:35.633
at rest.

00:00:35.633 --> 00:00:37.619
Creating it also mounts it,

00:00:37.619 --> 00:00:40.398
so it immediately becomes a folder with

00:00:40.398 --> 00:00:43.177
its own Docker daemon and isolated application

00:00:43.177 --> 00:00:43.574
data,

00:00:43.574 --> 00:00:45.560
completely separate from everything else.

00:00:48.560 --> 00:00:51.236
Repository created and already mounted on the

00:00:51.236 --> 00:00:51.618
server,

00:00:51.618 --> 00:00:52.765
ready to use.

00:00:56.094 --> 00:00:58.478
Let's confirm the new repo is registered.

00:00:58.478 --> 00:01:00.522
From here it can be deployed,

00:01:00.522 --> 00:01:00.863
forked,

00:01:00.863 --> 00:01:01.544
backed up,

00:01:01.544 --> 00:01:03.247
or opened in your editor,

00:01:03.247 --> 00:01:04.610
all from your laptop.

00:01:07.690 --> 00:01:10.090
There it is, registered and ready to use.

00:01:13.527 --> 00:01:14.557
One handy option:

00:01:14.557 --> 00:01:17.302
open the repo directly in VS Code with

00:01:17.302 --> 00:01:17.989
this command.

00:01:17.989 --> 00:01:20.048
We won't launch the editor here,

00:01:20.048 --> 00:01:22.794
but it starts a remote session into the

00:01:22.794 --> 00:01:25.540
repo over SSH so you can edit its

00:01:25.540 --> 00:01:25.883
files.

00:01:26.683 --> 00:01:29.359
Run that on your laptop to edit the repo's

00:01:29.359 --> 00:01:30.549
files in VS Code.

00:01:31.451 --> 00:01:34.571
That's your first repository, ready to go. Next

00:01:34.571 --> 00:01:36.731
up, we'll deploy an app inside it!
